Kannt <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caenn>Caenn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#333333>(2/18/03 10:54:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=96>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: idiot socialists</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>my question still does remain, if either of those scenarios did happen (maybe you're right, they won't), would America be ready to see the results?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And I realize that I didn't answer your question <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     .<br>
<br>
My response would be this: History has shown that the American people are willing to send their sons and daughters off to war when the cause is worth fighting for...and History has shown that the American people can suffer not having some of them return.  When the cause is worth fighting for.<br>
<br>
This <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a cause worth fighting for.  I get very frustrated because there is so much nonsense and plain BS floating around that tries to trivialize the reasons for which we are going to war (there is no might be...it's going to happen).  <br>
<br>
People in general do not care to really look in depth.  They get a glossed over version on the evening news and draw their conclusions from there.  There is nothing wrong with that, per se, as most people are not as passionate about things as I dare say we are.  The problem comes from the fact that a frightening amount of the information they use to make their decisions is either skewed, incomplete or flat wrong.  They see a couple talking heads present an argument on NBC Nightly News and their minds are made up.  Believe it or not, that would not bother me if the talking heads were ever unbiased and/or really knowledgeable.<br>
<br>
But as it happens people cannot make an educated decision as to whether they are willing to bear such a burden because the only information they get comes from people who either do not truly understand what they are talking about or (and this is much, much worse) DO understand yet espouse false rhetoric because they will do literally anything they can to win back voter support.<br>
<br>
Ahh, how I love (loathe) the two party system.<br>
<br>
Anyway, the two examples you gave just happened to be familiar refrains, and I guess I jumped at a chance to fire back at them.<br>
<br>
Silverblade:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Also get rid of him, he's one of the things kepeing the Islamic extremists DOWN. Wanna see a loony Islamic Iraq?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>This is exactly what I'm talking about!!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  This is at least the second time I've seen this argument put forth in this thread (might be more, I just don't remember) and I've still seen absolutely nil to substantiate it.  I've even mentioned in two separate posts that I would like someone to elaborate.  I really do want to be privy to whatever information you have that leads you to believe this, because until you can give some sort of evidence to back this claim, it is completely moot.<br>
<br>
Please...<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>please</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> give me some reasons as to why I should believe this.  I'm begging you.<br>
